INSERT INTO `wp_bb_posts` (`post_id`, `forum_id`, `topic_id`, `poster_id`, `post_text`, `post_time`, `poster_ip`, `post_status`, `post_position`) VALUES
(1, 3, 1, 3, 'It occurred to be me today that, had Tiger been born on his scheduled due date and then lived, he would be six months old. I think about age with Will too- usually when I see the child of a friend who was pregnant at the same time as me- and see what he would be. It’s strange but I can feel them in those moments- I can feel them in the empty space that they would inhabit had things gone another way.\r\n\r\nMy sister lost her second child Joseph just minutes after his birth- I was in my early 20s at the time. After we lost Will I sent her a card on Joseph’s birthday-something that I had never thought to do before- to say that I was at least comforted to know that Will would have his older 13-year old cousin to hang out with. She wrote back and said it was funny but she had never thought of Joseph as older than an infant until my card. Joseph would be 17, Will 4, and Tiger 6 months-. Do you all still count? Do you know the amount of time since you lost them or think about how old they would be?…. or are they always as they were to you?', '2010-04-07 18:23:30', '24.42.95.135', 0, 1),
(2, 4, 2, 3, 'We spend a lot of time talking about how much sensitivity to the differences in our losses should be highlighted on Hope In Loss. In the end I think we look to The Pregnancy Loss Support Group''s belief that: we all share the loss of a dream- we all share the loss of a baby, not matter the length of the pregnancy, not matter what came before or after.  \r\n\r\nThis is a quote from an interview with Elizabeth McCraken who wrote the book "An Exact Replica of a Figment of My Imagination". She was asked if she had not gotten pregnant so soon after the loss of her first child Pudding, would she feel differently about her loss- Did the birth of her second child make the future easier: \r\n\r\n"As far as wondering what life would be like without Gus--well, that feels as dangerous to me as wondering how life would be different if I hadn''t left Paris, or the United States, or if having insisted on seeing the midwife in the morning I''d insisted she send me immediately to the hospital, when my first child was still alive.  But I will say: having great joy come after great sorrow is easier on the heart than the other way around.  No doubt in my mind.  It doesn''t make the sorrow or the loss less, I want to say quickly, but--well, easier on the heart is the only way I can think of it.  A happier second marriage, security after wretched poverty.  It doesn''t matter.  Better to have your sorrow mitigated by joy than your joy rearranged by sorrow. \r\n\r\nBut as we said earlier, every little difference in biography changes the whole story.  Sometimes I wonder what it would be like to be a mother of a little baby and not absolutely obsessed with death.  I''ll never know.  On the other hand, I also will never know what it''s like to try to tend to one child while in the worst throes of mourning another; I will never know what it''s like to look at two children, one born Before and one born After and wonder what kind of difference that makes; I will never have to wonder what that sense of restoration, of feeling that the universe has bent back in favor to me, feels like."\r\n\r\nI post this because it represents what IS important- but doesn''t ultimately change our being here, as well as what is important and DOES matter most to HIL: our individual stories and differences are important but they do not separate us. The fact that we have all lost a child?- this is what is most important here because it is the heart of this space, it is the reason for our coming together- the children that we lost, and it matters because it is what binds us and offers us compassion in our differences. \r\n\r\nThis is the tone that I imagine for Hope in Loss.', '2010-05-17 16:45:53', '24.193.89.252', 0, 1),
(3, 4, 2, 2, 'My love -- I love how you have started this discussion -- we definitely have to continue it. What I think you capture so beautifully is, "all parents that have suffered the loss of a baby have suffered the loss of a dream." The rest is details. When I read what you wrote - I''m left thinking, we have all suffered a loss -- who? what? when? why? how? Who cares?\r\n\r\nI wonder if the Red Cross in Haiti took the time to ask people who had lost their homes, the size and shape of the rubble?\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, while none of the answers matter to me in this moment - in other moments - they seem to be the ONLY thing that matters. Maybe because the loss is the loss. It just is. How much more to think about there? Better to turn my attention to whether or not I should have stood quietly by while you screamed in the basement of the hospital. Better to seethe at the parent who makes the joke about loosing one of their living children!\r\n\r\nThe parents who come to this site will be in so wrecked --and the emotions will not be limited to sadness -- There will be sensitivity, there will be anger -- outrage even! jealousy -- despair -- what else?\r\n\r\nSomehow, Hope In Loss has to take it all in -- and create an environment where some small difference will be made... toward the positive. \r\n\r\nBut how?', '2010-05-17 20:03:33', '128.122.236.204', 0, 2),
(4, 3, 3, 3, 'I''m kind of amazed and confused by what I can and can''t handle these days. I hold a baby, I dash away from a woman on the subway carrying a newborn in a sling. I have a family with a 4 month old girl move into our house, I cry at little boy''s baseball games in the park. I wrote more about this on my blog space. But I''m wondering about you- has it changed for you-what you can handle? Does it ebb and flow or are you the same as a year ago?', '2010-05-19 15:24:12', '24.193.89.252', 0, 1),
(5, 5, 4, 1, 'Quick info for anyone that'' suffered the neo-natal loss of a child.', '2010-06-09 19:45:41', '128.122.236.204', 0, 1),
(6, 3, 1, 10, 'Teo would have been 6, just about 6 and  a half, but how I think of him is a bit of a contradiction.  On the one hand, he will always be a baby.  He is my forever baby suspended in time.  Then on the other hand, he is 6.  As the years have passed I often stop to imagine him as he may have been at the time.  He would have just been finishing up kindergarden.  What would he have loved?  Bugs, books, robots? When I see a boy and he is the age Teo would have been my breath is taken away and my heart skips a beat.  Would Teo have been that tall?  Would his hair have been so shaggy?  I do a lot of wondering.  If he is a winter baby, like my Teo, then I get the rock in the pit of my stomach and the lump in my throat.  How different their frigidly cold 2004 was.  I was in deep sorrow and they were soaring with joy.', '2010-06-18 00:38:26', '70.18.217.116', 0, 3),
(7, 3, 1, 5, 'Basil would be just over 14 months. All the wondering about ''what he would be doing now'' is both healing and torturous. On one hand, I''ll never really know when he would have learned to talk or walk; but on the other hand, all those thoughts continue to validate Basil''s humannes. He really did exhist--physically, not just in my thoughts and memories. \r\nI can relate to Ganna''s feelings of seeing other boys the same age as Basil would have been. Yes, those parents'' spring of ''09 was very different from ours. Their pregnancy was perhaps very similar, but then took a completely different path at delivery. I envy them. Most of the time when I see toddlers Basil''s age I am curious, but then must look away. It''s just so painful.\r\nIt''s odd and even magical, but I think there will always be two Basils in my mind: the newborn we held at the hospital and simultaneously the one that is growing (in my thoughts and love) that would be toddling around eating goldfish crackers by now.', '2010-06-24 17:35:51', '68.82.237.169', 0, 4),
(8, 3, 1, 3, 'I also think about the alternate world where my boys live Liisa (do all of us?)... the one where everything went fine and they are their age. Just yesterday this 4 1/2 year old boy joined us randomly in the park. His name was Oscar (Will''s name is Will because he was born early and well... you get it. Otherwise he would have been Oscar). He was so beautiful, this boy. I get that rock in my stomach too Ganna.... and then I stare like I''m watching a really familiar movie that I love so much, I never want it to end.... and yet when it does end I snap out of it and I''m emotionally exhausted.', '2010-06-28 17:29:47', '24.193.89.252', 0, 4),
(9, 4, 5, 3, 'Hello everyone. I wrote a draft of ''Thoughts for Friends and Family'' before we even met. I would love feedback so that I can incorporate your input and ask Melanie to edit it. It is one of the PAGES to the right here. If you have time to read it and add/comment/subtract please do that here. We can discuss anything points we are unsure of here. Thanks', '2010-06-29 13:45:44', '24.193.89.252', 0, 1),
(10, 5, 6, 2, 'I''m nearing the end of Elizabeth McCracken''s wonderful, An Exact Replica of a Figment of My Imagination. It''s about her journey through the loss of her son, Pudding.\r\n\r\nBut this topic and this post are not about the book. It''s about how reading the book made me feel. Wistful, sad, guilty, hopeful -- sometimes a wonderful melancholy that felt good and right -- other times a searing pain - like I was scratching a scab -- with salty fingernails. \r\n\r\nI love the book. I can''t wait to read the last ten pages, but here''s the rub: Yesterday I picked it up and started reading in a careless, "how can I kill ten minutes" kind of way -- because I''m, "reading a book" -- like you might do with a Grisham novel -- and I''m in a waiting room, waiting for my glasses to be ready.  So, I was reading about Pudding and I was suddenly caught up in something I wasn''t ready for -- a dark sadness, a really formidable and scary kind of pain, it was powerful and awful -- like the ocean''s undertow. And at the last second, I pulled myself back, closed the book and thought, "I don''t have the space right now, here at Pacific Optometry in Chinatown, to think about dead babies", -- not Elizabeth McCracken''s, not even my own. Then, I sat back in my chair, waited for my glasses, and settled into the familiar guilt of having disappointed, maybe even disrespected, my beautiful boys, Will and Tiger.\r\n\r\nSo here’s the topic: Do you ever feel like your grief is taking you someplace dark and ugly and you''re unsure if can, or should, pull out of it? If you did pull out of it - what went wrong or right? If you didn''t pull out of it, what went wrong, or right?', '2010-07-01 14:51:49', '128.122.236.204', 0, 1),
(11, 5, 6, 5, 'Oh geez, I can so relate. Elizabeth McCracken''s book was my favorite on the topic (It sounds dark to have a ''favorite'' babydying book, but after the dozens I''ve read, I have earned the right to have a favorite).\r\n\r\nSeveral of her chapters were read while at a 4th of July BBQ last year. One of the guests had arrived with a baby that HAPPENED to be Basil''s age and just HAPPENED to have their car seat carrier draped in the exact same lineny swaddling blanket we had given the funeral home to wrap our beloved son in. The horror. \r\n\r\nAll the BBQ guests cooed and danced around the new baby and (though they were well aware of what had happened to us just 3mo. prior) avoided bringing up any baby-related topics with us. The irony: I guess they didn''t want to ''upset'' us. As if seeing a baby the same age as ours with the same swaddling cloth our son was cremated in didn''t already ''upset'' us!\r\n\r\nI quickly felt the desperate need to excuse myself from the celebration of the new baby and literally ran to the front of the yard choking on tears. I spent the next few hours alone on the front steps with Pudding''s story. Reading someone else''s dark story was comforting in an eerie way--something about us not being alone in the darkness. I embraced it and it helped get me through the afternoon. (I was still scarred going to that damn annual BBQ again this year...but the pain was less horrifying.)', '2010-07-13 17:49:40', '68.82.237.169', 0, 3),
(12, 5, 6, 3, 'I feel so sad- not so much THAT a woman is pregnant- I''m saddest about the fact that I don''t feel that happiness at the wonder of it all, when I see that belly, anymore. And I get really stuck there. I''m thrown back to being pregnant one second, then I am the woman who will never be pregnant again, than I think about what is inside there.... and I''m sad about things that are just too sad to write. I''m tortured that I can''t smile at that woman with the warm congratulations eyes. \r\n\r\nMostly I pull myself back, quickly. It''s an art. Or I think I do and that I''m good at the art of it.... but every so often, later, I''m dark and quiet and my heart hurts. And that beautiful belly is why I''ll bet. \r\n\r\nI should pull myself back- really because- there is enough sadness. I do my grief work. I honor my boys. My life is altered. I doesn''t do any of us, including my boys, any good to dwell there. But, you know, it''s sticky.', '2010-07-14 18:23:31', '24.193.89.252', 0, 3),
(13, 3, 9, 3, 'The ebb and flow of sadness always takes me by surprise. I''m more grounded, compassionate, I laugh and am really dealing with the world here without my boys and then something reminds me..... and I''m back. Maybe not all the way back but to that place.... and it seems to happen in a moment. And then its as if I can''t recall that I''ve laughed for felt joy. I know I did but it''s like I''m looking at that part of life from an alternate universe. \r\n\r\nFor me it''s body memory. I dance really hard and get the adhesion pain back from my pregnancy and there you go. Or a pregnant woman. Or 1 year old boys in baseball hats. And the prevailing feeling is that empty place and longing. \r\n\r\nWhat are the things that remind you?', '2010-07-14 18:26:49', '24.193.89.252', 0, 1);
